iplomacy. Traditional approaches have failed to acknowledge the profound social, cultural and psychological impacts of diplomatic events, an imbalance that is redressed in this volume. Taking a range of national examples and using a variety of methods, The Munich Crisis, Politics and the People recreates the experience of living through the crisis in Czechoslovakia, Germany, France, Britain, Hungary, the Soviet Union and the USA.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aAdolf Hitler.  aBenito Mussolini.  aEdouard Daladier.  aEurope and the USA.  aMunich crisis.  aNeville Chamberlain.  aappeasement.  acrisis.  adiplomacy.  ahistory of emotion.  ainternational relations.  apsychoanalysis.  apublic opinion.1 aDrábik, Jakub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoeschel, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoethals, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorodetsky, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Julie V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Julie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeimann, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHucker, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHucker, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLojko, Miklos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreston, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShapira, Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToye, Ric